results.notes:
I found these specimens growing on moss right next to the river. There were dozens of them, growing either singly or in groups of 2 or 3. They caught my eye because at first glance they look like shiitake, but the substrate and other macroscopic features (as well as spore print) didn’t match.

Every one of them had the same fibrillous pattern on the cap: cluster of fibril spots, then a somewhat bare narrow ring, followed by a thicker ring of more compact fibrils and finally the shaggy edges in the cap.

A picture of the brown-cinnamon to rust-brown spore print is included, as well as the spores themselves and the measurements of the spores (thanks to Joe Matanzas). Pictures of younger and older specimens are also included.

Several genera have been explored, including Galerina, Lacrymaria, Cortinarius and Tubaria, but haven’t been able to pin point any.

results.notes:
These small critters (largest cap = 5-5.5 cm wide max) were growing gregariously in a scattered fashion in mixed deciduous woods dominated (at this spot) by beech. Other boletes posted earlier and to be posted have been found nearby.
All but one fruitbody in this collection came from the same spot. The sole basidiocarp – which came from a different place in the woods (mostly oaks) and, IMO, is possibly another taxon – can be distinguished from the rest in the photos by the smooth, darker and uniformly brown cap with no surface cracking and a “chipped” margin, the reticulated upper stipe and the cut stipe base; it sits in the lower left corner in the first four photos and in the upper right corner in the last two photos showing the cap surfaces. I forgot to pull it aside when removing collections from the bag. This sole fb is “Collection B”, whereas the remaining group is “Collection A”.
Ammonia on cap of the dominant taxon turned vivid green (26A8 = poison green/signal green in Kornerup & Wanschler), fading slowly to brown.

results.notes:
A few fruibodies scattered along a trail in mixed deciduous woods dominated by oaks and maples. The two fbs with larger caps were growing essentially next to each other (~1 yard apart), whereas the other one was found on the other side of the trail 5-7 yards away. I recall finding this species at WCSP 9 years ago, obs 70219, but – if memory serves right – it was in the woods on the other side of the creek, though not terribly far away from where the present collection was growing.
Note the variability in the appearance of the pileipellis: the color, the texture of the cuticle and the degree of surface cracking. The stipe surface was covered with these scruffy punctae or squamules and the lower stipe/base appears to have been coated with a white basal mycelium (I don’t think it’s mold). Context near the juncture of the stipe and cap slowly stained mottled pinkish/bluish/purplish and stayed this way for at least 10 minutes. notes_fields.Micro: Some gill tissue was mashed onto a slide with one drop of 4% KOH, and a photo of spores was obtained. A typical spore measured 19.3m x 13.2m. Within my limited experience, the spore size is unusually large.

If so, then presence/absence of types of cystidia agrees very well with the C du Q description of M. brevipes.

Stipe lengths slightly smaller than cap widths.

The stipes of these two mushrooms are approximately 4.5 cm. This is slightly larger than what is reported for M. brevipes. Also, the cap color is paler than what is expected for M. brevipes. Persistently dry/sunny weather is a potential explanation for pale cap surface.
